<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-23T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-23T06:00:00-05:00" n="850" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d850">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">840.48 Refugees/1929: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Jerusalem</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Steger</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Jerusalem</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-23T13:00:00+02:00">October 23, 1939—1
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 23—11:29 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>12. Immigration schedule for the period October 1, 1939 to March 31,
                                1940 published in <hi rend="italic">Official Gazette</hi> on October
                                19, provides for issuance during that time of 300 certificates for
                                non-Jews plus certificates as may be required for their dependents.
                                As reported in Consulate General’s despatch 1018 of July 21, Jewish
                                immigration for the period was suspended and no certificates for
                                Jews were authorized.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Steger</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>